Acknowledgments
At Just Above Midtown, collaboration and creativity
were the most valuable resources, sustaining the
gallery over its twelve-plus years. Likewise, this mul-
tifaceted exhibition could not have come together
without a shared effort to bring JAM's ethos into every
element of its preparation. We are grateful and
indebted to all involved.
First and foremost, we acknowledge and celebrate
our collaborator Linda Goode Bryant, a tenacious cat-
alyst for experimentation and discovery; her tireless
commitment to having fun together encouraged new
possibilities of exhibition-making at The Museum of
Modern Art. She gave us and our colleagues oppor-
tunities to engage in a close dialogue with a commu-
nity of artists, and we appreciate the trust she placed
in our ability to care for a history she built, which
inspires and challenges in our contemporary context.
On behalf of everyone who has worked with her-at
JAM, MOMA, or elsewhere-we are grateful for the
creative force that is Linda Goode Bryant.
We extend our utmost appreciation to the artists
in the exhibition and to former JAM staff who lent
their work or encouraged our research, often gener-
ously offering incredible memories that enriched the
project: Cheryl Banks-Smith, Dawoud Bey, Cathey
Billian, Willie Birch, Sydney Blum, Rolando Briseño,
Horace Brockington, Barbara Chase-Riboud, Albert
Chong, Gylbert Coker, Pat Cummings, Charles Daniel
Dawson, Marcy R. Edelstein, Wendy Ward Ehlers,
Tom Finkelpearl, Susan Fitzsimmons, Kathleen
Goncharov, David Hammons, Maren Hassinger, Reine
Hauser, Cynthia Hawkins, AC Hudgins, Hock E Aye
Vi Edgar Heap of Birds, Janet Olivia Henry, Suzanne
Jackson, Walter C. Jackson, Noah Jemison, G. Peter
Jemison, Jasper Johns, Nina Kuo, Valerie Maynard,
Jeanne Moutoussamy-Ashe, Senga Nengudi, Lorraine
O'Grady, Howardena Pindell, Liliana Porter, Jorge
Luis Rodriguez, Alva Rogers, Betye Saar, Raymond
Saunders, Coreen Simpson, Lorna Simpson, Lowery
Stokes Sims, Kit-Yin Snyder, Yasunao Tone, Kaylynn
Sullivan TwoTrees, Faythe Weaver, Tony Whitfield,
Randy Williams, Fred Wilson, and Martha Wilson,
and the friends, family, and champions of Charles
Abramson, Bimal Banerjee, Camille Billops, Vivian
Browne, Martin Cohen, Dan Concholar, Blondell
Cummings, Peter Feldstein, Howard Finster,
Lona Foote, Palmer Hayden, Norman Lewis, Freda
Leinwand, Rosemary Mayer, George Mingo,
Lawrence D. "Butch" Morris, Frank Parker, Sandra
Payne, Robert Rauschenberg, Vernon Reid, Greg Tate,
and Russ Thompson.
Our ability to exhibit work by JAM artists relied on
the generosity of several galleries and private lenders.
We are deeply grateful to Laurie B. Eichengreen and
W. H. Bailey, Doree Friedman Collection, Gochman
Family Collection and Forge Project, Alexander
Gray Associates, the Hatch-Billops Collection,
Hudgins Family Collection, Sean Kelly Gallery, Kravis
Collection, Andrew Kreps Gallery, Manneken Press,
Estate of Rosemary Mayer, Dr. Harold McDaniel and
Jeanette McDaniel, Ortuzar Projects, Sandra M. Payne
Trust, Michael Rosenfeld Gallery, Ryan Lee Gallery,
Robert Rauschenberg Foundation, Craig Robins
Collection, Charles White Archives, and Wyeth Na.
Collection.
We also extend our thanks to the institutions that
kindly lent their works and supported our research:
Addison Gallery of American Art, Phillips Academy;
Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution;
Brooklyn Museum; American Folk Art Museum; the
Governor Nelson A. Rockefeller Empire State Plaza
Art Collection; the Metropolitan Museum of Art;
Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago; the National
Gallery of Jamaica; Schlesinger Library, Harvard
Radcliffe Institute; The Studio Museum in Harlem;
and Virginia Museum of Fine Arts.
Additional gratitude is due to the colleagues and
friends who facilitated research, viewings, or loans
for the exhibition, including Valérie Rousseau at
the American Folk Art Museum; Susan Cary at the
Archives of American Art: Asma Naeem and Leslie
Cozzi at the Baltimore Museum of Art; Margaret
Rieckenberg at Barrett Barrera Projects; Loreta
Lamargese at Bortolami Gallery; Eugenie Tsai at the
Brooklyn Museum; Kinshasha Holman Conwill; Cary
Cordova; Dena Fisher; Amelia Russo and Candice
Hopkins at Forge Project; Erin Jenoa Gilbert; hal-
ley harrisburg and Michael Rosenfeld; Dion Hatch;
Vickiy Strutt-Hackman and John Hackman; Amanda
Stoffel at Hauser and Wirth; AC, Thelma, and
Lauren Hudgins; Liz Mulholland at Andrew Kreps
Gallery; Howard Mandel; Catherine Burns and Akili
Tommasino at the Metropolitan Museum of Art;
O'Neil Lawrence at the National Gallery of Jamaica;
Fabienne S. Powell at the New York State Office of
General Services; Ales Ortuzar, Kenta Murakami, and
Kari Rittenbach at Ortuzar Projects; Jeffrey Lee and
Ethel Renia at Ryan Lee Gallery; the friends and family
of Sandra Payne-Janet Goldner, Patricia S. Jones,
Kenisha Jones, and Valerie Knew; Karen Grimson
at Craig Robins Collection; Diana Carey at the
Schlesinger Library; Lorna Simpson Studio; Carolyn
Sommers; Kim Snyder; Connie Tilton; Nancy and
Richard Walch; and Charles White Archives, with our
deepest gratitude to lan White and Paulina Alvarez.
At MOMA, our foremost thanks go to Glenn D.
Lowry, The David Rockefeller Director, whose
ongoing support for this project allowed it to grow
from an idea into a reality. Associate Director
Sarah Suzuki was an integral thought-partner who
believed fiercely, providing indispensable advice
as we crafted a nontraditional infrastructure. We
are grateful to Ramona Bronkar Bannayan, former
Senior Deputy Director, Exhibitions and Collections,
whose early commitment and clever problem-solv-
ing allowed us o access the archival materials that
formed the backbone of this project. We are thank-
ful to Christy Thompson, Senior Deputy Director,
Exhibitions and Collections, for approaching each
element of this complex production with openness,
warmth, and a sense of possibility. We are also grate-
ful to Stuart Comer, The Lonti Ebers Chief Curator of
Media and Performance, for being our first and last
cheerleader, nourishing us with big ideas and the
day-to-day care needed to make them happen.
This project would not have come to fruition without
Margaret Aldredge-Diamond, Exhibition Manager: her
ability to use the structures at our disposal to respond
to the exhibition's various needs as well as her exem-
plary empathy were vital. Her colleagues in Exhibition
Planning and Administration, especially Erik Patton,
Jennifer Cohen, and Sarah Stewart, provided consis-
tent support and enthusiasm. Mack Cole-Edelsack,
Senior Design Manager, was our creative partner at
every step as we generated concepts for the exhibition
design and then tried to manifest them; his curiosity,
spirit, and humor were contagious. We thank Jessica
Nilsen, Associate Registrar, for her crucial support in
ensuring the utmost care of the artwork in our custo-
dianship, and Aaron Harrow, A/V Design Manager, for
his ingenuity in approaching media-an essential com-
ponent of this endeavor. Heidi Hirschl Orley, Assistant
Director, Curatorial Affairs; Robert Kastler, Director,
Imaging and Visual Resources; and Stefanii Ruta, Head
Registrar, kindly advised us and shared key insights.
at critical moments. James Grooms and Ava Childers
in General Counsel showed enthusiasm for working
closely with artists. Odessa Roberts Matsubara and
Laura Coppelli in Human Resources ensured the proj-
ect had proper staff support.
The history of improvisation we attempted to re-
create would not have been complete without live
performance. For their openness and trust, we are
grateful to the colleagues with whom we worked
closely on programming in The Marie-Josée and
Henry Kravis Studio. They include our Media and
Performance coconspirators Ana Janevski, Curator,
who has been at our side at every major crisis and
celebration, and the ever-insightful Martha Joseph,
Assistant Curator. In Performance and Live Programs,
Lizzie Gorfaine, Paul de Pietro, Kate Scherer, and
Olivia Rousey brought each performance to fruition
with inspiring dedication. We began this project
working with Ginny Benson, who sadly passed away
before the exhibition's completion; we miss her and
continue to light a candle to her creative force.
Our colleagues in Media and Performance, with
whom we share a small and collaborative workspace,
were our backbones, providing meaningful reflection,
administrative support, and a laugh when necessary.
We consider ourselves lucky that we regularly get to
see and learn from Rebecca Kusovitsky, Department
Manager; Chelsea Airey, Executive Assistant; Erika
Papernik-Shimizu, Associate Curator; and Gee Wesley,
Curatorial Assistant.
The Chief Curators-Christophe Cherix, Clément
Chéroux, Rajendra Roy, Martino Stierli, and Ann
Temkin-provided a foundation for this exhibition and
were our key interlocutors at various crossroads in
our planning. Thank you to Leah Dickerman, Director,
Research Programs, for creating space for the explo-
ration of ideas, and to curatorial colleagues, past
and present, who offered their invaluable expertise
and love for art and artists: Beverly Adams, Esther
Adler, Makayla Bailey, Sophie Cavoulacos, Emily
Cushman, Julia Detchon, Lucy Gallun, Sonja Gandert,
Lily Goldberg, Danielle Jackson, Jordan Jones,
Inés Katzenstein, Sam Kofodimos, Michelle Kuo,
Cara Manes, Sarah Meister, Piper Marshall, Veronika
Molnar, Oluremi Onabanjo, Paulina Pabocha, Carson
Parish, and Lanka Tattersall, who offered her reflec-
tions with depth and spark. Outside MOMA, Nicole
Acheampong is an inspiration.
We thank our colleagues in the David Booth
Conservation Department for their excitement and
curiosity about the wide range of mediums in the
exhibition. Peter Oleksik's patience and thought-
fulness were crucial to the presentation of archival
media works. Lee Ann Daffner, Michael Duffy, Tina
March, Annie Wilker, and Lynda Zycherman brought
their expertise to viewings, discussions, and consid-
erations of key works.
Our colleagues in External Affairs made intuitive
connections and built meaningful relationships that
created a financial base for this exhibition. We are
grateful to Meagan Johnson, Mallory Lenoir, Maggie
Lyko, Beverly Morgan-Welch, Dore Murphy, Mariana
Salem, and Nora Webb. We are profoundly apprecia-
tive of Amanda Hicks, Meg Montgoris, and Sara Beth
Walsh in Communications and Public Affairs, who
worked closely with us to communicate the stakes of
the show.
On the Creative Team, Kevin Ballon, Claire Corey,
Damien Saatdjian, and Christie Zhong took imagina-
tive risks in coming up with the graphic sensibility for
the exhibition. We thank Prudence Peiffer and her col-
leagues Emily Bahret, Isabel Custodio, Hanna Girma,
and Alison Knoll for their enthusiasm for sharing
the exhibition with various audiences. Sarah Cowan
worked closely with us on editing many of the videos
and films that appear both in the galleries and online.
Our colleagues in Learning and Engagement mod-
eled an approach to curatorial collaboration, which
was appropriate given Linda Goode Bryant's origins
in museum education. Sara Bodinson advised on the
oral history project and, along with Arlette Hernandez
and Oriana Gonzales, offered honest feedback on our
interpretive materials, encouraging us to make good
on our promise to organize a show that was acces-
sible to as many interested audiences as possible.
Jackie Neudorf helped shape the various voices of
the didactic materials into a unified chorus. Rachell
Morillo worked closely with Adelia Gregory, Brianna
Harlan, and Nisa Mackie to develop public programs
that aim to make space for the kind of unexpected
and riotous debate that flourished at JAM.
We extend deep thanks to the Department of
Archives, Library, and Research Collections, led by
Michelle Elligott, who went above and beyond to
assure that the Just Above Midtown Gallery Records
were accessible to our team for research and believed
resolutely in the importance of sharing JAM's history.
